'''Ethnic relations in India''' have historically been complex.  ("Ethnic relations" refers to attitudes and behaviours toward people of other [[ethnicity|ethnicities]] or [[Race (human categorization)|races]].)  India is extremely diverse ethnically, with more than 2,000 different ethnic groups.<ref>{{cite web|title=Background Note: India |author=US Department of State |date=17 April 2012 |url=https://www.state.gov/r/pa/ei/bgn/3454.htm |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120618165336/http://www.state.gov/r/pa/ei/bgn/3454.htm |archivedate=18 June 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>  Furthermore, within [[India]], there is also significant diversity within regions, and almost every [[Provinces of India|province]] has its own distinct mixture of ethnicities, traditions, and culture.  Throughout the history of India, ethnic relations have been both constructive (as with mutual cultural influences) and destructive (as with [[discrimination]] and ethnically-based violence).

==Constructive relations==
Usually, people in different regions respect each other's cultures and traditions.  According to local sources, [[unity in diversity]] has been growing in India, making the country more tolerant.<ref>{{cite news|title=Unity in diversity is basis for India|url=http://www.hindu.com/2010/01/09/stories/2010010954970700.htm|accessdate=|newspaper=The Hindu|date=9 January 2010|location=Dindigul, India}}</ref>

==Discrimination==

===Against North-East Indians===
In recent years there have been many reports of discrimination against people from [[North-East India]].  In 2007, the ''North East Support Centre & Helpline (NESC&H)'' was started as a separate wing of [[All India Christian Council]].  Its stated goal is to increase awareness regarding prejudice and attacks against people from North-East India.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nehelpline.net/?page_id=193|title=About NE Support Centre & Helpline|date=5 January 2011|publisher= North East Support Centre & Helpline|accessdate=14 August 2013}}</ref>  Many North-Eastern Indians face discrimination; are refused living accommodations when they travel to urban areas to study;<ref>{{cite news|title=Delhi won't lend a home to students from northeast|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/India-news/NewDelhi/Delhi-won-t-lend-a-home-to-students-from-northeast/Article1-1105466.aspx|accessdate=|newspaper=Hindustan Times|date=9 August 2013|location=New Delhi, India}}</ref> and are subjected to racial slurs<ref>{{cite news|title=Students from North East tired of discrimination|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/students-from-north-east-tired-of-discrimination-10607|accessdate=14 August 2013|newspaper=NDTV|date=26 October 2009|location=New Delhi, India}}</ref> in reference to the appearance of their eyes.  A spokesman for the NESC&H has stated that abuse and harassment of North-Easterners is increasing.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indiaedunews.net/in-focus/June_2009/Northeast_students_question_%27racism%27_in_India_8316|title=Northeast students question 'racism' in India|date=6 June 2009|publisher=India edunews|accessdate=13 August 2013}}</ref>

In 2012, in an attempt to prevent such discrimination, the Indian government asked all of its states and union territories to arrest anyone who commits an act of [[wikt: atrocity|atrocity]] against a North-Easterner under the [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes]] (Prevention of Atrocities) Act.  A person found guilty under this law can be jailed for 5 years.

In 2014, a North-Eastern student named Nido Taniam was [[Nido Taniam|killed in New Delhi]].

in October 2014, there were two separate incidents, one in which a North-East student was beaten by three men in [[Bangalore]] for not speaking [[Kannada]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/northeast-student-attacked-in-bangalore-allegedly-for-not-speaking-kannada-607174|title=Northeast Student Attacked in Bangalore, Allegedly For Not Speaking Kannada|author=Maya Sharma|date=15 October 2014|work=NDTV.com|accessdate=6 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/manipuri-student-leader-attacked-in-bangalore-told-speak-in-kannada/article1-1275549.aspx|title=Manipuri student attacked in Bangalore, 3 arrested|work=www.hindustantimes.com|accessdate=6 May 2015}}</ref> and a second where a North-East student was beaten by seven men in [[Gurgaon]], Haryana.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://in.news.yahoo.com/after-bangalore--it-s-gurgaon--n-e-students-brutally-assaulted-110501137.html|title=After Bangalore, it’s Gurgaon: N-E students brutally assaulted|date=16 October 2014|work=Yahoo News India|accessdate=6 May 2015}}</ref>

===Attacks on non-natives in Assam and other North Eastern States===
In Assam India, there have been many attacks on those from outside the region.  In 2007, thousands of [[Hindi]]-speaking labourers fled from Assam after a series of massacres and bomb attacks.  In May 2007, nine of them were killed and another 20 injured in violent attacks.<ref>Subir Bhaumik (23 May 2007). "[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/6683767.stm Persecution of Assam's Hindi speakers]". BBC</ref> The next month, 26 people from other parts of India were killed in a series of attacks over a period of six days. The police blamed [[United Liberation Front of Asom]] (ULFA) and the [[Karbi Longri N.C. Hills Liberation Front|Karbi Longri National Liberation Front]] for the violence.<ref>[[Wasbir Hussain]] (12 August 2007). "[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/08/11/AR2007081100464_pf.html 30 Killed in Northeast Violence in India]". Washington Post.</ref>  In response, the members of Purvottar Hindustani Sammelan (PHS) staged a [[hunger strike]] in [[Dispur]] to protest against the "merciless killings of innocent and defenceless Hindi-speaking people."<ref>[http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1321800621.html Hindustani Sammelan stages fast-unto-death]". Hindustan Times. 17 August 2007.</ref> Overall, 98 non-locals were killed in Assam during 2007.<ref>"[http://www.satp.org/satporgtp/countries/india/states/assam/data_sheets/militenetattack.htm Militant Attacks on Non-Locals in Assam]". SATP. Retrieved 4 February 2014.</ref>

In March and April 2008, a banned [[Meitei people|Meitei]] outfit killed 16 non-locals in Manipur.<ref>"[http://www.upi.com/Emerging_Threats/2008/04/18/Manipur-rebels-kill-Hindi-speakers/UPI-20441208560399/#ixzz2sIa9ZyjG Manipur rebels kill Hindi speakers]". UPI. 18 June 2008.</ref>  PHS alleged that anti-social groups in Assam were carrying out a continuous hate campaign against the Hindi speakers in the region.<ref>"[http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-allegation-of-harrassment-of-hindi-speaking-people-1171553 Allegation of harrassment &#91;sic&#93; of Hindi-speaking people]". DNA. 16 June 2008.</ref>

In May 2009, nine Hindi speakers were killed in Assam and Manipur, after the attackers set around 70 houses on fire.<ref>"[http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/nine-hindi-speaking-people-among-12-killed-in-northeast/article1-409905.aspx Nine Hindi-speaking people among 12 killed in Northeast]". Hindustan Times. 12 May 2009.</ref>

During 8–10 November 2010, 21 Hindi, [[Bengali language|Bengali]], and [[Nepali language|Nepali]] speakers were killed by a faction of the NDFB in Assam.<ref>"[http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/nine-attacks-since-monday-toll-now-22/708839/ Nine attacks since Monday, toll now 22]". Indian Express. 10 November 2010.</ref> 

In [[Meghalaya]], the non-indigenous people (who are collectively called ''Dkhars'') are often targets of militant groups.<ref>T. Haokip, "[https://www.academia.edu/2227014/Inter-Ethnic_Relations_in_Meghalaya Inter-Ethnic Relations in Meghalaya]", ''Asian Ethnicity'', 15:3, 302-316, DOI: 10.1080/14631369.2013.853545</ref>

